The title ‘Ars Poetica’, or ‘De Arte Poetica Liber’, is found in almost all MSS. Quintilian vm. 3, 60 writes id tale est mon- strum, quale Horatius in prima parte libri de arte poeticafingit: and in the Epist. ad Tryph. a (prefixed to his Institutio) says usus Horatii corintio, qui in arte poetica suadet, ne praecipitetur editio, nonumque prematur in annum. Later grammarians regu· larlyuse the same title, and it is employed also by Porphyrion and the socalled Acron. There is no evidence that it comes from Horace himself 3 it was probably invented by an early editor, and it is not very suitable to the contents of the epistle, {lsettletplelttedbrithtllltltttl{teht · be intentionally avoided. But a name which hasbeen so long in use cannot be abandoned without inconvenience3 and it may be accepted on the authority of tradition, provided we do not allow it to mislead us as to the real character of the epistle.
